# Power Automate workflow type decision matrix

## Purpose

This knowledge base helps users determine whether a workflow should be built as a **Power Automate cloud flow**, a **Power Automate desktop flow**, or a **hybrid** (cloud flow orchestrating a desktop flow). It also provides guidance on translating requirements into concrete workflow stages, actions, and connectors within the Microsoft 365 ecosystem.

When a user describes a process they want to automate, use the decision criteria below to recommend a workflow type, then use the workflow patterns section to suggest specific stages and actions.

---

## Decision criteria

Ask the user about their workflow requirements using the criteria below. Each criterion is labeled with an ID and a weight (1–3) indicating how strongly it signals one platform over the other. Higher weight = stronger signal.

### Desktop flow indicators

| ID | Criterion | Weight | When this applies |
|----|-----------|--------|-------------------|
| D1 | The process automates a legacy desktop application UI with no API or connector (SAP GUI, mainframe terminals, thick-client ERP, AS/400 emulators) | 3 | The target application has no web interface, no REST API, and no Power Automate connector. The only way to interact with it is by driving the UI — clicking, typing, navigating menus. |
| D2 | The process drives a locally installed application that has no API, no connector, and no web interface — pure RPA screen interaction is the only option | 3 | Similar to D1 but for any locally installed software. If the application has a web UI or API, a cloud flow with a connector is the better path. |
| D3 | The process requires triggering scanner or imaging hardware physically attached to a specific VDI or workstation | 2 | A physical scanner, barcode reader, or imaging device is plugged into a machine and the automation must trigger the scan and receive the output file. If documents are ingested upstream (scan-to-SharePoint, scan-to-email), a cloud flow handles it instead. |
| D4 | The process scrapes or interacts with web applications that lack APIs and require browser-level RPA (clicks, form fills, navigation) | 2 | The web application has no API, no export function, and no connector. The only way to extract or input data is by automating browser interactions. |
| D5 | The process must interact with command-line tools, batch scripts, or local PowerShell on a specific machine | 2 | The automation needs to run CLI commands, execute .bat/.ps1 scripts, or interact with terminal applications on a particular workstation or server. |
| D6 | The process involves Windows authentication dialogs, credential prompts, or security modals that cannot be handled via SSO or service accounts | 2 | Windows security prompts appear during the process that require UI-level interaction to dismiss or authenticate through. |
| D7 | Files live on an isolated machine not connected to the network — individual laptops or PCI/PII-segregated drives behind firewalls | 1 | The files are on a machine that cannot be reached via the On-Premises Data Gateway. Network-accessible drives (NAS, Azure Files, mapped network drives) are reachable via cloud flow + File System connector + gateway. |

### Cloud flow indicators

| ID | Criterion | Weight | When this applies |
|----|-----------|--------|-------------------|
| C1 | The process is triggered by Microsoft 365 events — new email, Teams message, SharePoint file upload, Planner task, Forms submission, Dataverse record change | 3 | The workflow starts when something happens in an M365 service. Cloud flows have native trigger connectors for all M365 services. |
| C2 | The process coordinates actions across multiple M365 services (e.g., SharePoint → Teams → Outlook → Planner → Dataverse) | 3 | Data or actions need to flow between two or more Microsoft 365 services in sequence or parallel. |
| C3 | The process requires approval workflows, multi-stage business process flows, or conditional routing based on user responses | 3 | One or more humans need to approve, reject, or route a request before the process continues. Cloud flows have built-in approval actions and business process flow support. |
| C4 | Human-in-the-loop steps are handled via Power Apps forms, adaptive cards in Teams, or listening/signal flows that resume after user submission | 2 | A human needs to provide input, make a selection, or fill out a form as part of the workflow. Power Apps forms and Teams adaptive cards replace the need for desktop UI interaction when humans need to participate mid-workflow. |
| C5 | The process integrates with third-party SaaS via REST APIs, custom connectors, or built-in Power Automate connectors | 2 | The workflow needs to read from or write to external systems like Salesforce, ServiceNow, SAP (via connector), Jira, DocuSign, Adobe Sign, or any system with a REST API. |
| C6 | The process must run unattended on a schedule or recurrence without a logged-in user session | 2 | The workflow runs daily, weekly, or on a cron-like schedule with no human present to trigger it. Cloud flows support recurrence triggers natively. |
| C7 | The process accesses network file shares, NAS drives, or Azure File Storage via On-Premises Data Gateway and File System connector | 2 | Files are on network-accessible storage. The On-Premises Data Gateway + File System connector allows cloud flows to read, write, and watch files on these shares without a desktop flow. |
| C8 | The process uses AI Builder or Copilot Studio for document processing, form extraction, text classification, or entity recognition | 2 | The workflow involves AI-powered steps like extracting data from invoices, classifying emails, processing forms, or using GPT-based prompts. These are cloud-native capabilities. |
| C9 | The process needs built-in error handling, retry policies, run history, and analytics across all executions | 2 | The team needs visibility into every run, the ability to configure retry on failure, and historical analytics. Cloud flows provide this in the Power Automate portal out of the box. |
| C10 | The process requires solution-aware deployment across environments (dev → test → prod) with ALM and version control | 2 | The workflow will be promoted through environments using managed solutions, and needs to participate in the organization's ALM lifecycle. |
| C11 | The process must scale across multiple users, departments, or geographies with shared ownership | 2 | The workflow serves a team, department, or organization — not a single user's workstation. Multiple people may own, edit, or monitor the flow. |
| C12 | The process benefits from parallel branching — multiple actions running simultaneously to reduce total execution time | 1 | The workflow has independent steps that can run in parallel (e.g., send a notification AND update a record AND create a task at the same time). |

